docs.abstract: Boeing’s chief executive, Dennis Muilenburg, testified before Congress for the first time since the crashes of two 737 Max jets that killed 346 people.
docs.snippet: Boeing’s chief executive, Dennis Muilenburg, testified before Congress for the first time since the crashes of two 737 Max jets that killed 346 people.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Boeing’s chief executive faced the grieving relatives of two deadly crashes of its 737 Max jet at an emotional congressional hearing on Tuesday, as senators pummeled him with questions about whether the company should have grounded the plane before the second accident. At times looking shaken, the executive, Dennis A. Muilenburg, said that if he could do it over again, he would have acted after the first crash, off the coast of Indonesia last October. “If we knew everything back then that we know now, we would have made a different decision,” he testified. He said Boeing officials had asked themselves “over and over” again why they didn’t ground the plane sooner.

headline.main: Boeing C.E.O. Knew About Pilot’s Warnings Before Second Crash
headline.print_headline: Boeing C.E.O. Had Warning Before a 2nd Crash

docs.abstract: The company had long maintained that the training wasn’t needed to fly the plane, which was grounded after two deadly crashes.
docs.snippet: The company had long maintained that the training wasn’t needed to fly the plane, which was grounded after two deadly crashes.
docs.lead_paragraph: From its inception, Boeing’s 737 Max was designed to save airlines the expense of training their pilots on flight simulators. During the initial approval of the plane and after two crashes killed 346 people last year, Boeing argued in conversations with the Federal Aviation Administration that simulator training was not necessary.

headline.main: In Reversal, Boeing Recommends 737 Max Simulator Training for Pilots
